/sergei-lebedev-untraceable.html\"><img src=\"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2021/01/21/books/21Lebedev-sub/merlin_182294442_9d21d105-e3fc-4500-a552-e27f43fdfa4c-jumbo.jpg\" srcset=\"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2021/01/21/books/21Lebedev-sub/merlin_182294442_9d21d105-e3fc-4500-a552-e27f43fdfa4c-jumbo.jpg 820w\" alt=\"“Not so many novels are written in terms of what is happening in Russia now,” Sergei Lebedev said. “The tragedies and the problems of the current moment are somehow ignored or avoided.”\"></a><figcaption><span><span>Credit</span>Mustafah Abdulaziz for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></article></li><li><ol><li><article><figure aria-label=\"media\" role=\"group\"><span>Photo</span><a data-rref=\"\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/20/books/review-doctors-blackwell-women-medicine-janice-nimura.html\"><img src=\"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2021/01/20/books/20BOOKNIMURA1/20BOOKNIMURA1-videoLarge.png\" srcset=\"https://static01.nyt.com/images/2021/01/20/books/20BOOKNIMURA1/20BOOKNIMURA1-videoLarge.png 768w, https://static01.nyt.com/images/2021/01/20/books/20BOOKNIMURA1/20BOOKNIMURA1-mediumThreeByTwo440.png 440w\" alt=\"\"></a><figcaption><span><span>Credit</span>.</span></figcaption></figure><div><h3>Books of The Times</h3><h2><a data-rref=\"\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/20/books/review-doctors-blackwell-women-medicine-janice-nimura.html\">Two Sisters Who Changed the Medical Profession</a></h2><p>In “The Doctors Blackwell,” Janice P. Nimura tells the story of Elizabeth and Emily Blackwell, physicians who became feminist figures almost in spite of themselves.</p><p><span><span data-testid=\"todays-date\" aria-label=\"19h ago\">19h ago</span></span><span></span><span>By<!-- --> <span>Jennifer Szalai</span></span></p></div></article></li><li><article><figure aria-label=\"media\" role=\"group\"><span>Photo</span><a data-rref=\"\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2021/01/19/books/review-copenhagen-trilogy-tove-ditlevsen.html